<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-314-828  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 314 828.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  May 29 1989 n419 p27(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Imaging users innovate. (image processing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moore, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users of image processing equipment have become more creative intheir uses of the technology.andP;  Image processing was originallydesigned as a massive file cabinet to store data not frequentlyaccessed.andP;  In most cases, users opted for image processing as thenumber of paper documents soared through available storage space.andO;However, users are now finding image processing systems as a meansof storing more immediate data such as manuals, personnel recordsand other large data files.andP;  Image processing systems use highcapacity optical disks to preserve graphic and text images ondisk, rather than in paper files.andP;  Image processing technology hasadvanced beyond primitive systems that required long waiting timesfor document access.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image ProcessingApplicationsInformation Storage and RetrievalDocument Management SystemsUser NeedsMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>